  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Open homes are information-rich events. The number of groups through, how long they stay, what they ask, and what they do not say all tell your agent something useful about buyer sentiment and the likely outcome of your campaign. For sellers, understanding what these signals mean gives you a clearer picture of how your campaign is tracking and whether any adjustments are needed before the next open.</p>

      <p>Not every signal is meaningful in isolation, but patterns across two or three opens start to tell a consistent story. A good agent will debrief you after each inspection with a clear, honest read. Here is what they should be looking for and what it means for your campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Attendance numbers</h2>
      <p>Attendance at an open home is a basic measure of whether your marketing has generated awareness and interest. In Brisbane's inner east, a well-priced and well-presented property in an active market should attract between 15 and 30 groups across a Saturday open home during the first two weeks of a campaign. Fewer than 10 groups consistently over two opens is a meaningful signal that something needs to be reviewed, whether that is the price, the marketing reach, the photography, or the timing of inspections.</p>

      <p>High attendance does not automatically mean strong buyer conviction. A busy open can be driven by curiosity, neighbours, and casual browsers. The quality of attendees matters more than the raw count. An open home that draws 8 genuinely motivated buyers who have already inspected comparable properties and understand the market is more valuable than 30 people who come through once and never contact the agent again.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be tracking both figures: total attendees, and the number who register genuine interest via a follow-up call or second visit.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Time spent inside</h2>
      <p>How long buyers spend in a property is one of the clearest behavioural signals an agent can observe. A buyer who walks through in four minutes, thanks the agent politely at the door, and leaves is highly unlikely to submit an offer. A buyer who spends 20 to 25 minutes, moves through the rooms twice, opens wardrobes, stands in the kitchen looking at the yard, and asks about the neighbours is actively building a mental picture of living there.</p>

      <p>Buyers who are seriously considering a property will often be seen measuring rooms, checking mobile reception, looking at the quality of fittings closely, and discussing the layout with their partner or family members. These behaviours are meaningful even if they do not result in an immediate question to the agent. A buyer who is measuring spaces has mentally moved past "would I buy this" and is working on "how would this work for us."</p>

      <p>An agent who is attentive at an open home should be able to identify the two or three buyers who spent the most time inside and were most engaged. Those buyers are the ones worth following up directly after the open.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers ask</h2>
      <p>The questions buyers ask during an open home are a direct window into their thinking. Questions about the contract, settlement dates, what is included, and whether the vendor has flexibility are buying signals. They indicate a buyer who has moved past consideration and is starting to work through the practicalities of ownership.</p>

      <p>Questions about what is wrong with the property, why it is priced the way it is, or how long it has been on the market are different in character. They may indicate a buyer who is skeptical about value or looking for reasons to discount. That is not necessarily a problem: a buyer who is doing their due diligence and pushing hard on price can still be your buyer. But your agent needs to understand the distinction between a buyer who is negotiating hard because they want the property and a buyer who is testing the market without real conviction.</p>

      <p>Questions about the neighbours, the street, the suburb's trajectory, and local schools indicate a buyer who is thinking seriously about the location as much as the property itself. These buyers tend to be committed and are worth nurturing through the campaign, even if they take more time to get to an offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Return visits and second inspections</h2>
      <p>A second inspection is the clearest signal of genuine buyer intent short of an actual offer. When a buyer asks to return for a private viewing, they have typically narrowed their shortlist and want to spend more time in the property with fewer people around. They may bring a parent, a builder, or a financial advisor. Each of these additions tells you something about where they are in the decision process.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be actively following up with every buyer who attended an open home within 24 hours. The purpose of that call is not to pressure anyone, but to ask a simple question: was there anything you wanted to see again or any questions I can answer? That prompt will often surface a request for a second inspection that the buyer was considering but had not acted on yet.</p>

      <p>Multiple second inspections across a campaign is a strong sign that your property is in genuine contention for several buyers. In that situation, the negotiation and closing process becomes the most important part of your agent's role.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What silence means</h2>
      <p>Silence from buyers after an open home is sometimes interpreted by vendors as polite disinterest, but it is rarely that simple. Buyers who attended and have not called back fall into several categories. Some have moved on to other properties. Some are waiting for more information. Some are discussing amongst themselves and will make contact when they have reached a decision. And some are genuinely interested but waiting to see what happens with the campaign before they commit to an offer.</p>

      <p>Silence in the first 48 hours after an open home is not unusual. If your agent has followed up with every attendee and the feedback is consistently non-committal or negative, that is worth taking seriously. If the feedback is mixed, with some buyers citing price as the issue, that is also information worth acting on early rather than waiting until week four of a campaign.</p>

      <p>One thing silence rarely means is that the open home was universally successful and offers are imminent. If buyers were strongly motivated, most of them will have made contact within the first 48 hours. Your agent should be able to give you an honest read on what the silence from specific buyers is likely to mean, based on their observations during the inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Using feedback to adjust your campaign</h2>
      <p>The feedback collected across the first two open homes is the most valuable input you have for deciding whether your campaign is on track. If attendance is strong but follow-up is low, the property may be generating curiosity without conviction, which often comes back to price. If attendance is low, the issue is typically in marketing reach or the timing and positioning of the property. If second inspections are happening but no offers are materialising, the gap may be between where buyers see value and where you have set your expectations.</p>

      <p>None of these are insurmountable, but they are best addressed early. A price that is 5% above where the market wants to engage becomes harder to recover from in week five than in week two. Listening honestly to the signals from your open homes, rather than waiting for the market to come around to your view, is one of the clearest ways to protect your result.</p>

